`.` is the workspace root for a zero-dependency Rust compiler that turns `dict.steno` (the single source of truth, read from this root by all three binaries) into four artifacts under `out/`: `plain.json`/`smart.json` for Plover and `plover-keys.json`/`snippets.json` for the `nvim/` plugin. The actual compiler lives in `crates/` (workspace containing the sole `steno` crate); everything else at this level is either input (`dict.steno`), consumer (`nvim/`), authoritative documentation (`docs/`), CI enforcement (`scripts/`, `.github/`), or unrelated meta-tooling for generating these `.ctx` files (`prompts/`).

`dict.steno`'s grammar (fences, directives, template operators) is re-implemented in `crates/steno/src/parse.ts`-equivalent parser code and re-described in `docs/steno-format.md`; a change to directive or operator semantics must land in the parser and, per `docs/rollup.ctx`, in `docs/steno-format.md`/`pipeline.md` together, or the corpus and docs silently diverge. `nvim/` depends on `build-nvim`'s two JSON outputs as a matched pair — regenerating one without the other breaks token matching — and treats their sentinel/wire format as the compiler's export contract, not something to work around locally. `scripts/ci.sh` is the single aggregate gate (fmt, clippy, doc, deny, machete, plus repo-local checks) that any change to `crates/`, `dict.steno`, or `docs/` must pass; `.github/` exists only to invoke it on push/PR.

Cross-cutting invariants stated in `intent.md` and echoed in `README.md`/`docs/pipeline.md`: dataflow through the compiler is one-way (`stroke ← parse ← expand ← {editor, render, snippet, blocks}`, no back-edges), errors are typed and never swallowed, and the three binaries write only under `out/` and only after stroke-collision checks pass — a collision aborts with no partial output. `Cargo.lock` currently locks zero dependencies, consistent with the no-runtime-dependencies non-goal.

`prompts/` and the ctx-tooling it drives are infrastructure for maintaining these `.ctx`/`rollup.ctx` files themselves and sit outside the compiler's dataflow entirely; nothing in `intent.md` covers or needs to cover them.